              <p>The information patterns in the LDN <a href="#specification">specification</a> and the <a href="linked-data-notifications#test-suite-and-implementation-reports">implementation reports</a> sections are reusable across other specifications and related components. Sources are available from:</p>

              <ul>
                <li>The specification: <a href="https://www.w3.org/TR/ldn/">https://www.w3.org/TR/ldn/</a></li>
                <li>The test suite: <a href="https://linkedresearch.org/ldn/tests/">https://linkedresearch.org/ldn/tests/</a></li>
                <li>Implementation reports summary and individual reports: <a href="https://linkedresearch.org/ldn/tests/summary">https://linkedresearch.org/ldn/tests/summary</a></li>
              </ul>

              <p>The test suite uses the <cite><a href="https://github.com/csarven/mayktso">mayktso</a></cite> server as the LDN receiver, but any conformant receiver implementation will work here.</p>

              <p>The missing connection among existing specifications and test reports is that a uniform resource discovery is not possible between the test reports and the individual conformance criteria in the specifications, where a given information at a particular URL is both human and machine-processable (see <cite><a href="http://csarven.ca/linked-specifications-reports#related-work">related work</a></cite>.)</p>

              <p>The key takeaways are:</p>

              <ul>
                <li>Human and machine-readable documents via HTML+RDFa are feasible for specifications and implementation reports.</li>
                <li>The connection between EARL and the QB vocabulary is suitable for multi-dimensional data without having to define new component specifications for the data cube.</li>
                <li>Individual observations (test results) can be identified and discovered through contextual links in the specification, with the use of EARL and QB vocabularies.</li>
                <li>The LDN protocol can support the possibility to send, receive and consume notifications about the implementation reports, as well as help with their discovery and reuse.</li>
                <li>It is possible for other documents to refer to specific parts of the specification, test suite and reports.</li>
              </ul>

            </div>
          </section>


            </div>
          </section>



          <section id="linked-research-forces-functions" inlist="" rel="schema:hasPart" resource="#linked-research-forces-functions">
            <h2 property="schema:name">Forces and Functions of Linked Research</h2>
            <div datatype="rdf:HTML" property="schema:description">
              <p>The forces and functions of scholarly communication in context of the Linked Research design principles are define below .</p>

              <p id="linked-research-forces">The <em>forces</em>:</p>

              <dl>
                <dt>Actor</dt>
                <dd>Any <q cite="https://www.w3.org/TR/webarch/#def-web-agent">web agent</q> — person or software — is able to participate in scholarly communication using WebIDs.</dd>

                <dt>Accessibility</dt>
                <dd>The retrievability and reusability of registered units can be determined by actors with access controls.</dd>

                <dt>Content</dt>
                <dd>Actors shape their content as Linked Data as well as offer suitable presentations and interactions in which the registration refers to.</dd>

                <dt>Applicability</dt>
                <dd>The need and relevance for research and their application can be mined from available other content.</dd>
              </dl>

              <p id="linked-research-functions">The <em>functions</em>:</p>

              <dl>
                <dt>Registration</dt>
                <dd>The ecosystem permits any actor to register units of communication by associating a URI to new or nonexistent resources.</dd>

                <dt>Awareness</dt>
                <dd>Actors share and consume registered units.</dd>

                <dt>Certification</dt>
                <dd>Annotation with any motivation, replying, commenting, reviewing</dd>

                <dt>Archiving</dt>
                <dd>Any actor can trigger the archiving process to create snapshots of the content of registered resources.</dd>
              </dl>

              <!-- <p>We will revisit these functions later in the thesis as a technical response to Sompel's call to investigate <q cite="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=o4nUe-6Ln-8&amp;t=2792">how to fulfil the core functions of scholarly communication using the technical paradigm</q> around self-publishing.</p> -->

            </div>
          </section>



          <section id="contextualising-linked-research" inlist="" rel="schema:hasPart" resource="#contextualising-linked-research">
            <h2 property="schema:name">Contextualising Linked Research</h2>
            <div datatype="rdf:HTML" property="schema:description">
              <p>LR is an initiative to strive to experience the full effects of the Web by observing and making use of its affordances. It serves as a conceptual framework that describes how actors can control their interactions and data, as well as how decentralised and socially-aware applications can exchange information.</p>

              <p>Are there ideological and technology traps? The traps can be seen as analogous to McLuhan's <q>reverses into</q> effect. When the LR design principles are pushed to the extreme, highly specialised and fine-grained centralised systems can and will emerge while still operating within the larger decentralised system on the Web. The degree of federation or interoperability among the autonomous systems will vary. The effects may be that of a new generation of third-party control and authority over certain information spaces. For example, just as centralised publishing and distribution services currently exist for the dominating paper-centric industry, the medium can still accommodate similar control over semantic and granular scientific resources. It is worthwhile to note that the ecosystem would only become more diverse as it expands. Entropy is an inherent property of the Web.</p>

              <p>It is worthwhile to note here that the existing models for information exchange that has been described so far primarily focus on institutional or subject repository driven scholarly communication. They are contrasted against the involvement of third-party (for-profit) service providers which impose a particular arrangement of the coupling of the scholarly information space per <em>forces and functions</em>. In the remainder of this thesis, I focus on enabling a <strong>researcher-centric</strong> model; whilst this can be situated within the same <q>deconstructing</q> or <q>decoupling</q> school of thought, its pursuit is embracing greater control by content creators through the native characteristics of the Web, without interfering with the certification function regardless of the academic discipline; humanities, social, natural, formal, or applied sciences. The notion of content creators or consumers having some control on accessibility, registration and archiving, inherits certain qualities of coupling. That is, researcher-centric coupling unleashes the potentials of expressivity and effective scholarly communication.</p>

              <p>While the criteria for publishing provided by <cite>Genuine Semantic Publishing</cite> is valuable and can also be exercised by following LR's <q>interpretable</q> design principle, we do not prescribe it in order to not conflict with the <q>freedom of expression</q> principle. If a third-party imposes a specific way to express knowledge, whether it is through file formats and their structure and semantics; what (meta)data to include or not include; or inclusion and use of interactive components; the quality of the communication is subject to be less effective because the author may have to make compromises. Information loss occurs and communication quality naturally degrades simply because what the actors wish to convey in their message, and how, will have to be filtered down in order to fit the requirements of a third-party, data formats, or user interfaces.</p>

              <p>At the time of this writing, LR's principles and the strive for interoperable systems is conceived within the Web paradigm, as opposed to the broader Internet. There are emerging technologies and platforms within the Internet which are highly specialised for security, versioning, distributed, and so forth, which give way to new possibilities on how the scholarly communication market can be realised. While this thesis fits LR's principles into particular contemporary technology stacks, this is for practical purposes and to demonstrate what can be achieved today. Nothing prevents the principles from being adopted under different environments. It is quite likely that the design philosophies of the new environments will differ.</p>

              <p class="todo">What is the scope? What are some of the instabilities or inadequate use of the system? What is missing or could use more development/attentions?</p>

              <p class="todo">We all produce and distribute information. It is our part of our nature. What kinds of rules would serve everyone's (writers and readers) needs in the Web environment? What may be the constrains?</p>


              <p>LR does not deconstruct scholarly publishing, but that it ironically indicates instead the need for a counter-environment as a means of practising the dominant and unnoticed environment.</p>


              <p>One of the effects of LR is that it is an attempt to formalise what is considered to be "informal" communication due the typical coupling of the functions by third-parties in scholarly communication.</p>

              <p>Sooner or later we need a strategy to address questions like: <em>What do we aim to accomplish?</em> <em>Who is trying to do it and for the benefit of whom?</em> <em>How do we know whether we are making progress and when we have succeeded?</em></p>

