              <p class="todo">Why this will never happen: promotion and tenure are integral to the academic profession. The incentives in the academic profession predominantly relies on an ecosystem that is largely led by third-party publishers and services. The proposed work does not address or replace the reputation problem. The importance of Open Science is on the rise, from social media, to increase in <a href="https://osf.io/7jbnt/">academic jobs that mention</a></p>


<p id="role-of-institutions"><strong>Role of Institutions</strong>:
* what roles could libraries/institutions play? eg notify about article/review
* institutional repositories like eprints then they buy PURE from Springer.
* ldprints</p>

              <p>Potential solutions to these questions and new challenges need to address the connection and the gap between researchers, academic and public institutions, as well as what ends up in the commons. It is not just about researchers making their contributions available on the Web, or about conferences requesting semantically annotated contributions, or operating with transparent peer-review. All of these things must move in combination. Some of the kinds of actors in the ecosystem to address fulfilling the the LR principles can be along these lines:</p>

              <dl>
                <dt id="cooperating-researchers">Researchers</dt>
                <dd>Researchers take full responsibility of their contributions. This can be at any Webspace they put trust on or have sufficient authority over, eg. personal site, institutions’ student and faculty pages. Making their work as <q>Webby</q> as possible eg. linking their arguments and citations to others', interactive story-telling or experimentation possibilities for their readers to be learnable. Researchers can take special care to ensure URI persistence and archiving of their work.</dd>

                <dt id="cooperating-conferences-and-journals">Conferences and Journals</dt>
                <dd>In person conferences and online journals should encourage and accept research publications which use native Web standards and technologies. Support transparent and attributed peer-review process. Aggregation or proceedings of the events can be machine-friendly and archival measures should be taken in addition to those of researchers.</dd>

                <dt id="cooperating-public-institutions">Public Institutions</dt>
                <dd>Given sufficient evidence of the Web Science community’s acknowledgement of research as well as its contributions, eg. peer-reviews, academic institutions can officially acknowledge such work towards academic credit. Libraries can  make the community’s output discoverable, catalogued, enriched, among many other things.</dd>
              </dl>

              <p>Mention https://communitywiki.org/wiki/DoOcracy https://web.archive.org/web/20181231115548/https://communitywiki.org/wiki/DoOcracy ?</p>


              <p>This section is about how we realise/enable the social changes technically, whilst still adhering to the LR principles (ie. why we can't just use twitter/easychair for academia etc).</p>
              <p>Point at the social parts of the Control Yourself chapter (AP, AS2, LDN) and say how these fit into the ecosystem. How they mean we can do the things people need to do in scholarly communications in a way that meets the principles.</p>
              <p>This is where we bring the decentralisation stuff back home to in-practice scholarly comms.</p>

              <p>There are different approaches to 'fixing' the ecosystem. We could try a wholehearted replacement of the current system. That's unlikely to succeed. We could try to directly change existing players (like publishers, conferences) and demand that they do things differently. Also probably not gonna happen. It might be better to work *alongside* existing practices, and gradually ease scholars into new ways of operating. our goal is not necessarily to replicate major academic publishing houses or academic social networks..  smaller, personalised connected components might be both easier to realise and more effective in the long run. But.. who knows.</p>


