          <section id="framing-our-vocabulary" inlist="" rel="schema:hasPart" resource="#framing-our-vocabulary">
            <h3 property="schema:name skos:definition">Framing our Vocabulary</h3>
            <div datatype="rdf:HTML" property="schema:description" resource="#framing-our-vocabulary" typeof="skos:ConceptScheme">
              <p datatype="rdf:HTML" property="skos:definition">The terms we use shape our frame of mind than. We adopt the idea that scholarly calls for <strong>contributions</strong> welcome researchers to <strong>share</strong> their <strong>articles</strong> with the community. We can adopt substitutions along these lines:</p>

              <dl rel="skos:hasTopConcept">
                <dt about="#s-submit-share" id="s-submit-share" property="skos:prefLabel" rel="skos:topConceptOf" resource="#framing-our-vocabulary" typeof="skos:Concept"><samp>s/submit/share</samp></dt>
                <dd about="#s-submit-share" datatype="rdf:HTML" property="skos:definition">Researchers <em>share</em> their scientific contributions as opposed <em>submit</em>.</dd>

                <dt about="#s-submission-contribution" id="s-submission-contribution" property="skos:prefLabel" rel="skos:topConceptOf" resource="#framing-our-vocabulary" typeof="skos:Concept"><samp>s/submission/contribution</samp></dt>
                <dd about="#s-submission-contribution" datatype="rdf:HTML" property="skos:definition">Researchers make <em>contributions</em> to the field as opposed to calls receiving <em>submissions</em>.</dd>

                <dt about="#s-paper-article" id="s-paper-article" property="skos:prefLabel" rel="skos:topConceptOf" resource="#framing-our-vocabulary" typeof="skos:Concept"><samp>s/paper/article</samp></dt>
                <dd about="#s-paper-article" datatype="rdf:HTML" property="skos:definition">Researchers create discoverable and accessible Web <em>articles</em> as opposed to documents that mimic <em>papers</em>.</dd>
              </dl>
            </div>
          </section>




          <section id="objectivity-value-judgment-and-theory-choice" inlist="" rel="schema:hasPart" resource="#objectivity-value-judgment-and-theory-choice">
            <h3 property="schema:name">Objectivity, Value Judgment, and Theory Choice</h3>
            <div datatype="rdf:HTML" property="schema:description">
              <p class="todo">Should this be discussed in Evaluation, Linked Research or Conclusions .. if at all?</p>
              <p>Kuhn's five characteristics, <q cite="https://web.archive.org/web/20180619083836/https://iweb.langara.bc.ca/rjohns/files/2018/03/Kuhn_theory_choice.pdf">accuracy, consistency, scope, simplicity, and fruitfulness</q> in <cite><a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20180619083836/https://iweb.langara.bc.ca/rjohns/files/2018/03/Kuhn_theory_choice.pdf">Objectivity, Value Judgment, and Theory Choice</a></cite>, ... and justify why the <cite>Linked Research</cite> design principles describes a paradigm that can be further investigated towards genuine scholarly communication on the Web.</p>

              <p><strong>Accuracy</strong>:</p>
              <p><strong>Consistency</strong>:</p>
              <p><strong>Scope</strong>:</p>
              <p><strong>Simplicity</strong>:</p>
